The U.S. War on Chinese Technology
NEW YORK — — One of the worst foreign policy blunders made by Americans (and their predecessors) was the 2003 invasion of Iraq, which was justified as a "war of choice" with the stated goal of eliminating — in reality, nonexistent — weapons of mass destruction.
The necessity of understanding the flawed logic behind that disastrous decision is now more critical than ever, given that the same logic is being deployed to defend similarly misguided American policies today.
The decision to invade Iraq was made under the flawed logic of then-Vice President Richard Cheney, who argued that even though the risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into the hands of terrorists was small (for example, 1%), we should act as if it were certain to happen.
But this mode of reasoning almost always leads to bad decisions.
However, the US and some of its allies are now using Cheneyism to attack China's technology.
According to the US government, since we cannot confidently say that Chinese technology is safe, we should treat it as definitely harmful and ban it.
The correct decision would apply probabilistic estimates to various alternative measures.
A generation ago, US policymakers should not only have considered the 1% risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into the hands of terrorists but also taken into account the 99% risk based on multiple flawed premises for launching a war.
By simply emphasizing that 1% risk, Cheney (as well as many others) diverted public attention away from the fact that the Iraq War was actually unjustified and would severely undermine political stability in the Middle East and globally.
But the problem with Cheneyism is not only that it acts on minimal risks without considering the extremely high potential costs, but also that politicians always stoke fear for some ulterior motives.
This is what US leaders are doing again: by pointing out and exaggerating certain minimal risks to instill panic about Chinese tech companies.
The case most relevant (but not the only one) in this regard is the US government's attack on the telecommunications tech company Huawei.
The US is gradually closing off its domestic market to the company and is trying to strangle its global business.
Like Iraq, the US may ultimately cause a groundless geopolitical disaster.
I have worked in developing countries and have always been attentive to the technological advancements made by Huawei because I believe that 5G and other digital technologies can provide significant impetus for eradicating poverty and achieving other United Nations Sustainable Development Goals.
I have also engaged in similar interactions with other telecom companies and encouraged the industry to take action towards achieving the sustainable development goals.
I wrote a brief foreword (unpaid) for a report Huawei had written on this topic, which led to criticism from those hostile to China. In response to this, I asked industry leaders and government officials if there was any evidence to suggest that Huawei had behaved improperly, and the repeated answer was that Huawei's conduct was no different from that of other trusted industry leaders.
Nevertheless, the U.S. government still believes that Huawei’s 5G equipment may compromise global security.
U.S. officials claim that "backdoors" retained in Huawei software or hardware could enable the Chinese government to engage in surveillance on a global scale.
They point out that Chinese law requires Chinese companies to cooperate with the government for national security reasons.
But here is the reality now.
Huawei's 5G equipment is cheap and of good quality, currently leading many competitors and has already been rolled out.
Its high performance comes from significant investments in R&D over many years, economies of scale, and experience navigating China's digital market.
Given the importance of this technology to their sustainable development, low-income economies around the world would be unwise to delay the rollout of 5G.
However, despite lacking any evidence of backdoors, the US is still persuading the world to avoid Huawei.
The US position is universal.
As one US Federal Communications Commissioner put it, "Countries that have 5G will be at the forefront of related innovations and set standards for the rest of the world, and that country is unlikely to be the US."
Other countries – particularly the UK – have not found any backdoors in Huawei's hardware and software.
Even if backdoors were discovered in the future, they would almost certainly be closed off then.
Debates over Huawei have also been raging in Germany, as the US government threatened to cut intelligence cooperation unless authorities kept Huawei's 5G technology out.
Perhaps under pressure from the US, the head of Germany's Federal Intelligence Service recently made a statement akin to Cheneyism: "Infrastructure is not an area where untrustworthy groups should be allowed to participate."
And he failed to present any concrete evidence of wrongdoing.
In contrast, Chancellor Merkel has been fighting behind the scenes to open the market to Huawei.
Ironically, much of the US complaints reflect its own surveillance activities at home and abroad – though this is nothing new.
The Chinese equipment could make it more difficult for the US government to carry out secret surveillance.
However, any government's illegitimate surveillance activities should be stopped.
Independent monitoring by the United Nations to reduce such activities should become part of the global telecommunications system.
In short, we should opt for diplomacy and institutional safeguards rather than engage in a technological war.
The threatening impact of the US demand to ban Huawei not only hinders the early deployment of 5G networks but also poses a significant risk to rules-based trading systems.
Now the United States is no longer the global uncontested technological leader, and President Trump and his advisers did not want to compete within a rules-based framework.
Their goal was to contain China's technological rise.
They also tried to paralyze the dispute settlement mechanism of the World Trade Organization to erase the organization, which similarly reflects their approach to global rules.
If the Trump administration "succeeds" in dividing the world into different technological camps, the risk of conflict in the future could multiply.
After World War II, the United States promoted open trade, which not only improved global efficiency and expanded the U.S. technology market but also reversed the collapse of international trade in the 1930s.
&#1;And part of the reason for the collapse was the protectionist tariffs imposed by the United States under the Smoot-Holley Act of 1930, which exacerbated the Great Depression and contributed to Hitler's rise, eventually leading to the outbreak of World War II.
Just as in other fields, instilling fear and acting on that fear—rather than following the evidence—is a path to destruction in international affairs as well.
Let us stick to reason, evidence, and rules—the safest course.
Let us establish independent monitoring bodies to reduce the threat of any country using global networks to spy on others or to launch cyber wars.
This way, the world can quickly leverage breakthrough digital technologies to achieve global welfare.
